  "title": "Mars",
  "content": "<p><strong>Mars</strong>, also known as&nbsp;<strong>Sol VI</strong>, is the fourth planet within the Sol system. Located within the Hydian Sector, it was the first planet visited and colonized by Humanity other than Earth. Early in its geological history, Mars supported large bodies of water that gave rise to simple lifeforms. By the time of Human colonization, it's oceans had largely evaporated and native life had gone extinct, save for a small handful of hardy single celled organisms. It has two small natural satellites, Phobos and Deimos.</p><p>Terraforming began in the late 21st century CE, and was successful in both restoring Mars' oceans and creating a breathable atmosphere. However, terraforming was left incomplete after extensive nuclear bombardment in 2263 resulted in the death of all Human life on the planet.</p><h1>Astronomical Information</h1><p>Mars orbits its star, Sol, at a distance of roughly 230 million kilometers (~1.66 AU). Within the Sol system, it was one of the four inner planets that orbited inside of Sol's asteroid belt.</p><h3>Climate and Geography</h3><p>Mars is a class-C terrestrial planet with the additional designation of class-TA. Mars has undergone three major climatic cycles in it's history. The first, ending approximately 3.8 million years ago, was dominated by a large liquid water ocean on the planet's northern hemisphere. During this time, the atmosphere was thicker, mainly due to evaporation from the ancient ocean. The second — occupying most of the planet's geological history — was an arid, nearly dead world with a thin, largely carbon dioxide based atmosphere; an archetypical class-C planet.</p><p>Shortly after the first permanent Human settlement in the late 21st century, terraforming began, aiming to turn Mars into a more habitable world for Earth-based life. Notably, this was the first large scale terraforming project undertaken by Humanity. Icy comets and asteroids were redirected into the planet, and artificial magnetic shielding was set up to protect the planet from cosmic radiation, allowing for Mars to support liquid oceans again. With the oceans re-established, marine plant life was introduced from Earth to build up an oxygen atmosphere. Along with nitrogen imported from the nearby moon of Titan, Mars developed a breathable oxygen-nitrogen atmosphere over the course of a century, officially ending in the 2240s.</p><p>Plans to complete the terraforming process by introducing terrestrial plant and animal life from Earth were interrupted by the United Systems civil war. Following the war's rapid escalation after the destruction of Earth in 2261, Mars was subject to a massive orbital nuclear bombardment that successfully killed all Human life on the planet. Mars experienced a three-decade long nuclear winter that rendered the planet entirely uninhabitable, poisoning the oceans and reversing much of the greenhouse effect that had been achieved by terraforming.</p><p>Prior to terraforming, the average global surface temperature was -76 °F (-60 °C). After terraforming, but prior to nuclear bombardment, Mars reached it's highest average global surface temperature, at 54°F (12.2 °C). The current average surface temperature fluctuates near 35 °F (1.6 °C). Mars has maintained sizable ice caps in its polar regions for it's entire geologic history.</p><p>Approximately 42% of Mars' surface is covered in water, mainly concentrated in the large ocean that takes up most of the northern hemisphere. Mars is notable for it's extreme geography; it boasts both the tallest mountain, Olympus Mons, and deepest canyon, the Valles Marineris, in the Sol System. It is a geologically active world, with multiple supervolcanoes (including Olympus Mons) dotting its surface.</p><h1>Flora and Fauna</h1><p>filler</p><h3>Human Settlement</h3><p>filler</p><p><br></p>",
